    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Analysis of Credit Appraisal of SME Loans Fulfillment of Masters Degree in Business Administration</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">M.Balaji</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Credit Appraisal<br />Loans Fulfillment</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">May-2012 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">P5856</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">The banking industry in India, through a measured, gradual, cautious and steady process, has undergone substantial transformation. As the economy transcends a higher growth path, and as it is subjected to greater opening and financial integration with the rest of the world, the banking sector will need considerable development, along with corresponding measures to continue regulatory modernization and strengthening. Regulators, policy makers and banks would have to work together for making sure that the growth engine for Indian economy functions smoothly and paves way for the country to become a global economic super power.
The Credit Management department is created in order to reinforce the Banks credit culture that it has built up carefully over the past years, as well as to meet the regulatory requirements specified by Bank of Baroda.
The department is committed to ensure that the credit approval procedures and practiced is consistent with the bankâ€™s lending principles and policies, thereby meeting the objective of maintaining the balance between operational efficiency and quality of assets and further, the recommendation for prevention or enhancement .
Risk Management Division has the responsibility for the designing of the credit risk management strategy, development of the credit and market risk policies and procedures through identification of risks, measurement of risk exposures through establishments of models/ systems and active monitoring of risk exposures on a portfolio basis. The Risk and Credit Management Division, which is an independent function reporting directly to the General Manager of the Bank has the overall responsibility for the identification , measurement, monitoring and control of the credit and market risks of the Bank.
The Head Office bears the responsibility of controlling the risks. Therefore, various techniques are adopted there. At the branch level, only selected techniques are adopted.
The larger the corporate segment, the greater the number of banks used. This means stiff competition between banks in this segment of medium/large companies and the major challenge for banks to provide high standards of service quality to ensure customer loyalty.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/11155">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/11155</a></td></tr>
